function excelSheetCells(s) {
    const [part1, part2] = s.split(':');
    const [c1, r1] = [part1.charCodeAt(0), parseInt(part1.slice(1))];
    const [c2, r2] = [part2.charCodeAt(0), parseInt(part2.slice(1))];

    const result = [];

    for (let c = c1; c <= c2; c++) {
        for (let r = r1; r <= r2; r++) {
            result.push(String.fromCharCode(c) + r);
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

    1. First, parse the input string `s` to extract the column and row values for c1, r1, c2, and r2.
2. Initialize an empty result list to store the cells.
3. Loop through the columns from c1 to c2.
  a. Loop through the rows from r1 to r2. 
    i. Append the cell string formed by concatenating the current column and row to the result list.
4. Return the result list with all the created cells.

